
    MUNICIPALITIES still owing outstanding money for water have committed to coughing up.Minister of Water and Sanitation, Nomvula Mokonyane, issued an update on the status of the pending water punishment facing defaulting municipalities.The debt for bulk water services nationwide is R10,7 billion.Sputnik Ratau, the department’s spokesman, said Mokonyane was encouraged by the positive response from 25 of the 30 most indebted municipalities.The five municipalities to face water restrictions are Ngaka Modiri Molema, Msukaligwa, Madibeng, Mafube and Maluti-a-Phofung.“Water restrictions will be implemented starting with a minimum of 20% reduction until payment arrangements are made with the department and the water boards or otherwise, increasing incrementally,” he said.Ratau said to date, a total of R213 million had been paid to the water boards and R55,5 million to the Water Trading Entity of the department.“Commitments received, over and above money already received, amount to R300 million. We would like to reiterate that payment for water services will go a long way towards addressing the water challenges facing the country.”if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");var viewReq = new Array();function vu(u) {var i=new Image();i.src=u.replace("&amp;","&");viewReq.push(i);}vu("https://securepubads.g.doubleclick.net/pcs/view?xai\x3dAKAOjssPriSWcHo81GU9QNP5Arw6NiVaiRPMez2X7ZA14UV_AbQQsQDRkaz5-GBEUYiPP7Ik5isW39odyMrSgJtPelxDjvhJIDdnPLiRgvtn4YYtqPxCubaPFFtgBeoaTPD6yO2mn6fx3IUEbxqIucnbBHWV4NhFDTYzovZ77hDuQqTu-Egd8mxoU0ES90deIl543UKlQroj-8dHGbn5E_mqBey5_2oHoNR0J3ao-tL6n5HdP_oW5nTCOBMtSxhtzCPoh2gI2n8H35Fh6TYD0u28b8K885BAfxE\x26sig\x3dCg0ArKJSzEhLoLSzA_6rEAE\x26urlfix\x3d1\x26adurl\x3d")

   
